<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALEMANY SHRUGS OFF ROAD DISADVANTAGE, BLITZES RIVAL ST. BERNARD, 57-37 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KENNEDY COSGROVE, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It's rare indeed when a basketball team swaggers into the gym of its chief 
rival -- ranked among the top teams in California and possessing two players 
who have already signed with Pacific 10 Conference schools -- and dispatches 
that team by 20 points. 
</P>
<P>
 But Tuesday was such a night for the Alemany High girls' basketball team. 
</P>
<P>
 Serving notice to the rest of the state that they, too, are a force to be 
feared, the Indians blew past seventh-ranked St. Bernard, 57-37, in a Mission 
League game at St. Bernard. 
</P>
<P>
 "We showed that we're a lot more experienced this year than last year," 
Alemany Coach Melissa Hearlihy said. "Last year they beat us twice." 
</P>
<P>
 Alemany, ranked sixth in California by Cal-Hi sports, improved to 15-0, 3-0 in 
league play, thanks primarily to a strong effort by post players Zevette 
Mitchell and Carly Funicello.  
</P>
<P>
 The duo combined for 22 points in the first half and badly outplayed St. 
Bernard's heralded 6-foot-4 senior tandem of Olympia Scott and Marte Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
 Scott, who has signed with Stanford, and Alexander, committed to by Arizona, 
did not score in the first quarter and combined for only 14 points the rest of 
the way. 
</P>
<P>
 Mitchell, Alemany's 6-foot senior forward, outscored them by herself, 
finishing with 18 points and 10 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
 "Zevette stepped up and had the best game of her life," Hearlihy said. "We 
needed to have a big day inside and we did." 
</P>
<P>
 Said Mitchell: "Last year I was intimidated against St. Bernard. Tonight I 
felt confident shooting-wise. Everything was pretty cool." 
</P>
<P>
 Funicello, a 6-foot-3 sophomore center, had 10 points in the first half, and 
finished with 12 points, eight rebounds and two blocked shots before fouling 
out in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
