<P>
PEOPLE: ATLANTIC RECORDS MAKES GOLDBERG OFFICIAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES BATES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In a move that had been expected for months, Atlantic Records on Tuesday 
officially named Danny Goldberg its president. 
</P>
<P>
 The move has been one of the music industry's worst-kept secrets since word 
that it was coming first leaked out last fall.Goldberg, 43, plans to relocate 
to New York next week. 
</P>
<P>
 "My main goal is to not screw up what already is a very strong and healthy 
company," Goldberg said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
 Atlantic is part of Time Warner's Warner Music Group. Goldberg fills a post 
left vacant in 1990 when Doug Morris moved up to become co-chairman/co-chief 
executive of Atlantic Group, a title he shares with label founder Ahmet 
Ertegun.  
</P>
<P>
 Atlantic has been one of Time Warner's hotter labels recently, scoring 
especially big with the success of the Stone Temple Pilots. It is also expected 
to announce soon an exclusive deal with veteran producer and composer David 
Foster. 
</P>
<P>
 Goldberg started his career as a rock journalist, working for such 
publications as Billboard, Rolling Stone and Circus, where he was editor. He 
later served as vice president of Swan Song, Led Zeppelin's record company. 
JAMES BATES 
</P>
</TEXT>
