<HEADLINE>
<P>
PERSONAL VIEW: EXECUTIVE TRAVEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Barbara Geraghty 
</P>
<P>
 * Name: Barbara Geraghty 
</P>
<P>
 * Position: President 
</P>
<P>
 * Company: Idea Quest, Irvine 
</P>
<P>
 In my sales training and motivational speaking business, I travel several 
times a month. Having an organizational plan is essential, so I have a list of 
everything that needs to be done as I prepare for a speaking engagement. 
</P>
<P>
 Included on my "to do" list:  
</P>
<P>
 * Call the hotel in advance and ask if it supplies hair dryers in the room, so 
I won't waste valuable luggage space.  
</P>
<P>
 * Ask about fitness facilities and whether or not I can go running safely, so 
I can pack proper workout clothing. 
</P>
<P>
 * Check the buttons on all clothing. Often a button has been knocked off when 
my suits have been cleaned for a trip. To find a button missing after leaving 
can be disastrous. 
</P>
<P>
 * Put one- and five-dollar bills in a separate envelope to use for tipping 
porters and bellhops.  
</P>
<P>
 * Make a packing list. The list includes everything I might possibly need for 
any trip. Each time I travel and discover something else I need, I add it to 
the list. When I pack, I simply go down the list. 
</P>
<P>
 Do you have advice for fellow business travelers or a travel-related 
experience you would like to share? Please mail your typewritten contribution 
to Executive Travel, Los Angeles Times -- Business News, Times Mirror Square, 
Los Angeles CA 90053. Or fax it to (213) 237-7837. Or send it electronically to 
3666973@mci-mail.com on the Internet. Please be as detailed as possible and 
include your name, title, company and a daytime phone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
